Observation of Red Wine Data Set by Renel Garces

This report includes the examination of the red wine data set. The main focus of this report is to find common characteristics that are shared between the same quality of wines. There will also be analysis conducted to observe the correlation between different variables to wine quality.

Univariate Analysis

What is the structure of your dataset?

The structure of the data set includes 1599 observations with 13 different variables.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

The main feature of interest in this report is to view the trends among different wines grouped by quality.

What other features in the dataset do you think will help support your
investigation into your feature(s) of interest?

I believe that there will be a negative relationship between acidity(pH) and quality as it’s generally thought that higher quality wines have lower the pH. I also hope to find that the wines containing the highest and lowest residual sugar values will be classified under lower quality ratings as I presume that those wines will be classified as low quality due to the imbalance of sweetness.

Did you create any new variables from existing variables in the dataset?

No

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions?
Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form
of the data? If so, why did you do this?

The only normally distributed variables were density and pH. All other variables appeared to be long-tailed and skewed towards the right.

In order to tidy the data, I adjusted the binwidths on plots with variables such as pH, citric.acid, and residual.sugar because the data points consisted of data that was calculated to the tenth or hundredth decimal place. This was to prevent rounding of the data that would cause the plots over cluster the data and make it difficult to see the variations in the distributions. I also limited the values along the x-axis on some of the plots in order to focus the plots towards the bulk of the data and ignore the outliers.

Bivariate Analysis

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the
investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in
the dataset?

After analyzing different relationships between different variables in the data set, it has been discovered that a lot of the variables were weakly correlated to the variable of quality including; acidity, sugar, chloride, density, sulphates unless you correlate the mean value of each variable in relation to quality. Mean residual sugar showdd the weakest correlation to quality while mean sulphates showed the strongest correlation to quality.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features
(not the main feature(s) of interest)?

I observed the correlation between citric acid content and overall pH. It was the highest positive correlation observed at 0.97. It was also interesting to see how little sugar had to do with the quality ratings.

What was the strongest relationship you found?

The strongest relationship found was the correlation between sulphates and quality rating at 0.9859.

Multivariate Plots Section

This plot’s purpose is to illustrate the mean composition of different quality wines in terms of acidity and sugar. There appears to be no trend between pH and sugar composition among the different quality of wines.

This plot shows that sugar does not increase as alcohol content increases. It also shows that higher quality wines tend to have more alcohol than lower quality wines.

Multivariate Analysis

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the
investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of
looking at your feature(s) of interest?

The relationships observed in the multivariant analysis included the observation of sugar and pH content among different qualities of wine, the combination of alcohol and sugar content among the different wine qualities, and the mean chloride and pH level among different wine qualities. The main takeway from the previous three plots is that it is difficult to see a distinction between sugar content and the quality of wine even when paired with other variables such as pH, chloride content, and alcohol content.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?

When all three plots are examined together it is revealed the residual sugar content would play little if any role being able to predict a wines quality. It was also interesting to see the high quality wines and low quality wines both shared the characteristic of containing relatively high amounts of sugar. The differentiating factor may be the sugar content in higher quality wines is balanced out by the higher alcohol content.

Final Plots and Summary

Plot One

Description One

This plot shows the distribution of different citric acid levels between low quality wines and high quality wines. The low quality wines are wines rated from 3-5 while the high quality wines are rated 6-8. The distribution of low quality wines appear to be slightly more weighted to the lower citric acid levels while the higher quality wines appear to be slightly more weighted to the higher citric acid levels.

Plot Two

Description Two

This plot was created to see if sugar and alcohol balance had anything to do with a wine’s quality. This plot reveals sugar is irrelevent to a wines quality given its alcohol content. The plot also reveals that higher quality wines tend to contain more alcohol relative to lower quality wines.

Plot Three

Description Three

This plot illustrates the strongest correlation in the data set which is the relationship between wine quality and sulphate amount. I added the median line in the graph to provide more statistical evidence that sulphate is strongly, positively correlated with wine quality.

Reflection

Overall this project opened to my eyes to how trends may not be as easily visible by looking at the raw data. Trends may be hidden because of the skewing caused by the over dispersion of data, the overcrowding of data points, or approaching the data itself in the wrong way. At first I struggled to find any meaningful relationships when I looked at the data with minimal manipulation. Once I’ve gotten to seperating the data set into different groups by wine quality and looking at the means of the other variables, it became easier to see trends and relationships. It was suprising to see that, despite my prediction, there was no trend in combinations of variables of pH and sugar, acidity and sugar, and alcohol and sugar when it came to predicting wine quality. I thought that higher wine qualities would share similar characteristics of a balance of sweet/salty, sweet/acidic, or sweet/alcohol. I was wrong. In the future, one may further examine this data set by taking an even sample from each wine quality group and conduct analysis of the variables to make up for the unequal representation of each wine quality in the data set.
